objects.name: Valak InfoStealer Being Distributed Using Compromised Email Accounts

custom_objects.collectionTitle: Valak InfoStealer Being Distributed Using Compromised Email Accounts
custom_objects.collectionWikiContent:
Summary
Campaigns delivering the Valak information stealing malware are using compromised email accounts to target victims. According to researchers from Cisco Talos, activity from these campaigns, which began in early 2020, spiked in significantly in May and June.
Threat Type
Malware
Overview
Valak is a relative newcomer to the world of information stealing malware. Attackers have been distributing the malware since approximately mid 2019. Valak is modular and described by Cisco Talos as having a robust feature set. Beginning in early 2020, campaigns using compromised email accounts began primarily targeting the banking, insurance, manufacturing and transport sectors with spikes in activity occurring in May and June. The attackers send reply emails to the recipients in existing email threads, the emails have a password protected ZIP file attached with the password being provided in the body of the email. These emails have been observed in multiple languages and in a number of different countries. The ZIP files contain a malicious Word document which, if opened, will seek to have the victim enable macros. Once enabled, the macros are used to download a DLL file, usually from an attacker controlled server located in Russia or Ukraine. The DLL is then registered and executed and will ultimately install the Valak malware. Talos researchers note that Valak is often seen on systems with secondary payloads of Gozi and IcedID. Unlike the narrow geographic locations of the hosts serving the malicious DLL, the C&C servers are more widely distributed across Europe, North America, the Asia Pacific and Africa. Further information is available from the report linked in the Reference section below.
Indicators of Compromise
See the Reports section to the right for the IoCs.
Recommendations
Ensure anti-virus software and associated files are up to date.
Search for existing signs of the indicated IoCs in your environment.
Consider blocking and or setting up detection for all URL and IP based IoCs.
Keep applications and operating systems running at the current released patch level.
Exercise caution with attachments and links in emails.
Reference
https://blog.talosintelligence.com/2020/07/valak-emerges.html
